#### 1.1.3 The mole & Avogadro's Number

One mole is defined as the amount of substance that contains as many elementary particles as there are atoms in 0.012 kg (12 g) of carbon-12 isotope.

The Avogadro constant N\({}_{\text{A}}\) is the number of atoms in 0.012 kg of carbon-12 isotope, and has been determined to have a value of \(6.02\times 10^{23}\) mol-1.

Hence, one mole of a substance contains \(6.02\times 10^{23}\) particles.

The mass of 1 mole of substance is known as the **molar mass** of the substance expressed in g mol-1.

Since there are N\({}_{\text{A}}\) particles in 1 mole of any element, the mass of an atom for a given element is

\[m_{\text{atom}}=\frac{\text{molar mass}}{\text{N}_{\text{A}}}\]

As such, _molar_ quantities refer to physical quantities associated with 1 mole of a substance. As an example, the molar volume of CO\({}_{2}\) means the volume occupied by 1 mole of CO\({}_{2}\) and so on.

